<WRITING SEX="MALE" PERSON="WRITER"><ORLANDOHEADER TYPE="text"><FILEDESC><TITLESTMT><DOCTITLE>Hilaire Belloc: writing</DOCTITLE></TITLESTMT><PUBLICATIONSTMT><AUTHORITY>Orlando Project</AUTHORITY></PUBLICATIONSTMT><SOURCEDESC>Based on original research by members of the Orlando Project.</SOURCEDESC></FILEDESC><REVISIONDESC><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KAH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>1 June 1998</DATE><ITEM>Initial document given to tagger.</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="KAH" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>30 July 1998</DATE><ITEM>added some better dates--could get more</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="PDC" WORKSTATUS="RWT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>6 October 1998</DATE><ITEM>Updated for Sept 1998 Audit</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>21 December 1999</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily orgName and bibCit cleanup</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="DRG" WORKSTATUS="REV" WORKVALUE="C"><DATE>1 February 2001</DATE><ITEM>converted textual apostrophes and quotation marks to entity references</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>14 April 2003</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily PLACE cleanup</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>16 June 2003</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: primarily TGENRENAME cleanup, BIBCIT following P moved before P, BIBCITS TAG added</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY><RESPONSIBILITY RESP="SYS" WORKSTATUS="CFT" WORKVALUE="I"><DATE>08 April 2005</DATE><ITEM>BATCH CHANGE: March 2005 Specifications. Mainly tag/attribute name changes</ITEM></RESPONSIBILITY></REVISIONDESC></ORLANDOHEADER><DIV0><HEADING>Writing</HEADING><STANDARD>Belloc, Hilaire</STANDARD><DIV1><DIV2><PRODUCTION><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>November 1896</DATE><CHRONPROSE>HB published the first of his six books of children&apos;s verse, entitled <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Bad Child&apos;s Book of Beasts</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Drabble and Stringer 47">Drabble and Stringer 47</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 65">Parker 65</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Cahill 9">Cahill 9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>Among his others were <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">More Beasts for Worse Children</TITLE> (1897) and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Cautionary Tales for Children</TITLE>, <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">[d]esigned for the admonition of children between the ages of eight and fourteen years</QUOTE> (November 1907).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 65">Parker 65</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC">BLC</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Cahill 16">Cahill 16</BIBCIT></BIBCITS> The admonitory aim was ironical.</P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>March 1896</DATE><CHRONPROSE>HB published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Verses and Sonnets</TITLE>, a book of comic rhymes.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Drabble and Stringer 47">Drabble and Stringer 47</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 65">Parker 65</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Cahill 9">Cahill 9</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>April 1902</DATE><CHRONPROSE>HB published a travel book, <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Path to Rome</TITLE>, which contained his own illustrations and sketches.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Drabble and Stringer 47">Drabble and Stringer 47</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 65">Parker 65</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Cahill 12">Cahill 12</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>1908</DATE><CHRONPROSE>HB published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Mr Clutterbuck&apos;s Election</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Drabble and Stringer 47">Drabble and Stringer 47</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 65">Parker 65</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>1911</DATE><CHRONPROSE>HB published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Eye-Witness</TITLE>, subtitled <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Being a series of descriptions and sketches in which it is attempted to reproduce certain incidents and periods in history, as from the testimony of a person present at each.</QUOTE></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 65">Parker 65</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC">BLC</BIBCIT></BIBCITS><SCHOLARNOTE><P>Drabble and Stringer (47) say that he founded the journal <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Eye-witness</TITLE> in 1911. BLC does not confirm this, neither does Parker. Cahill lists both the book listed here and the journal of the same title, which Belloc founded, and edited for one year.</P></SCHOLARNOTE></CHRONSTRUCT><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATERANGE FROM="1906--" TO="1910--" EXACT="BOTH">1906-1910</DATERANGE><CHRONPROSE>HB worked as literary editor for the <TITLE TITLETYPE="JOURNAL">Morning Post</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Drabble and Stringer 47">Drabble and Stringer 47</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 64">Parker 64</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>1911</DATE><CHRONPROSE>HB published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The French Revolution</TITLE>.<KEYWORDCLASS KEYWORDTYPE="French Revolution">politics</KEYWORDCLASS></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Drabble and Stringer 47">Drabble and Stringer 47</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 64">Parker 64</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>He published numerous books on historical subjects including <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">A Companion to Wells&apos;s <QUOTE DIRECT="Y">Outline of History</QUOTE></TITLE> (<DATE>1926</DATE>), <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Joan of Arc</TITLE> (1929), <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><NAME>Napoleon</NAME></TITLE> (1932), and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Monarchy: A Study of <NAME STANDARD="Louis XIV, King">Louis XIV</NAME></TITLE>.</P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>October 1912</DATE><CHRONPROSE>HB published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Servile State</TITLE>, a non-fictional satire on Edwardian society.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Drabble and Stringer 47">Drabble and Stringer 47</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 64">Parker 64</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="BLC">BLC</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Cahill 24">Cahill 24</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>1915</DATE><CHRONPROSE>HB published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The History of England</TITLE> covering the period from the first Roman invasion to the accession of <NAME STANDARD="George V, King">George V</NAME>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Drabble and Stringer 47">Drabble and Stringer 47</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 65">Parker 65</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>9 September 1920</DATE><CHRONPROSE>HB published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Europe and Faith</TITLE>.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Drabble and Stringer 47">Drabble and Stringer 47</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Cahill 31">Cahill 31</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><SHORTPROSE><P>HB, who often worked with fellow Catholic author <NAME>G. K. Chesterton</NAME> on campaigns against socialist humanist writers such as <NAME STANDARD="Wells, H. G.">Wells</NAME> and <NAME STANDARD="Shaw, George Bernard">Shaw</NAME>, wrote many books on religious topics. Others include <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Religion and Civil Liberty</TITLE> (1918), <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Jews</TITLE> (1922), <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">England and the Faith</TITLE> (1925), and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Catholic Church and History</TITLE> (1926), and <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">The Catholic and the War</TITLE> (1940).<BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 65-6">Parker 65-6</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></P></SHORTPROSE><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>1928</DATE><CHRONPROSE>HB published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Belinda</TITLE>, a novel which received a good deal of critical praise.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Drabble and Stringer 47">Drabble and Stringer 47</BIBCIT><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 65">Parker 65</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>1935</DATE><CHRONPROSE>HB published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><NAME STANDARD="Milton, John">Milton</NAME></TITLE>, a study of the author.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 65">Parker 65</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>1942</DATE><CHRONPROSE>HB published <TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC">Elizabethan Commentary</TITLE> the last work of non-fiction which he published before his death.</CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 66">Parker 66</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT><CHRONSTRUCT RESP="KAH" CHRONCOLUMN="WRITINGCLIMATE" RELEVANCE="SELECTIVE"><DATE>1953</DATE><CHRONPROSE><PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY><TITLE TITLETYPE="MONOGRAPHIC"><FOREIGN REG="Good Death" LANG="Latin">Bona Mors</FOREIGN></TITLE>, a collection of short stories, was HB&apos;s last work of fiction: the title means Good Death.</PLASTLITERARYACTIVITY></CHRONPROSE><BIBCITS><BIBCIT PLACEHOLDER="Parker 65">Parker 65</BIBCIT></BIBCITS></CHRONSTRUCT></PRODUCTION></DIV2></DIV1><WORKSCITED><SOURCE>British Library OPAC</SOURCE><SOURCE>Cahill, Patrick. The English First Editions of Hilaire Belloc. 1953.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Drabble, Margaret and Stringer, Jenny, eds. The Concise Oxford Companion to English Literature. 1987.</SOURCE><SOURCE>Parker, Peter, ed. A Reader&apos;s Guide to Twentieth Century Writers. 1996.</SOURCE></WORKSCITED></DIV0></WRITING>